## ADDENDUM 1 — ROOT CAUSE CORRECTION + FIX-0 SCOPE CHANGE (2026-06-10)

**Issued by:** Bishop SEG diagnostic (parallel SEG, BP080, 2026-06-10)
**Applies to:** SEG-V0147-DIAG-1 interpretation + SEG-V0147-FIX-0 scope

> **HARD-BINDING CORRECTION — read before executing any remaining FIX-0 work.**

---

### Root cause correction — DIAG-1 interpretation was wrong

The smoking gun in DIAG-1 read:

> `FAIL  binary NOT found at C:\Users\Administrator\AppData\Local\Programs\MnemosyneC\resources\ollama\ollama.exe`

**Original interpretation:** "installer doesn't bundle it."

**Corrected interpretation:** "installer DID bundle it, but Windows Defender silently removed it post-install."

A parallel Bishop SEG 7z-extracted `MnemosyneC-Setup-0.1.46.exe` and inspected the `app-64.7z` payload directly. Findings:

- `ollama.exe` is present in the installer payload at **35.6 MB**.
- Full bundled model is present at **379.4 MB**.
- `dist:win` pipeline (`prepare:ollama-binary` + `extraResources`) is **correct**.

The binary is inside the installer. It arrives on disk after install. Then it disappears. This is not a packaging bug — it is a **Windows Defender / SmartScreen silent quarantine** triggered because:

1. `ollama.exe` is unsigned (no code-signing certificate).
2. It lives in `AppData\Local` — a Defender hot zone for unsigned executables.
3. It opens a network socket (`ollama serve` on port 11434) — a Defender heuristic flag for unsigned processes.

Knight's FIX-0 work already shipped (assertion script, `publish:win` script fix, `asarUnpack` note — see below) is **not wrong** — it is good defense-in-depth. But the core P0 cause is Defender quarantine, not packaging.

---

### SEG-V0147-FIX-0 — RESCOPED

**Old scope:** Packaging audit — find why binary is missing from NSIS payload.

**New scope:** Defender exclusion — inject exclusion at install time so the binary survives post-install.

#### (a) `installer.nsh` — Add Defender exclusions in `customInstall` macro

```nsis
nsExec::Exec 'powershell -NonInteractive -Command "Add-MpPreference -ExclusionPath \"$INSTDIR\resources\ollama\""'
nsExec::Exec 'powershell -NonInteractive -Command "Add-MpPreference -ExclusionPath \"$INSTDIR\resources\""'
nsExec::Exec 'powershell -NonInteractive -Command "Add-MpPreference -ExclusionProcess \"ollama.exe\""'
```

**Knight must check installer mode first.** If `perUserInstall=false` (admin install), `Add-MpPreference` will succeed. If per-user (no admin elevation), `Add-MpPreference` may fail silently. In the per-user case, the installer MUST also display a UI dialog with the manual exclusion commands as fallback, so the user can run them themselves:

```
Windows Defender may block the bundled AI engine.
To fix, run in PowerShell (admin):
  Add-MpPreference -ExclusionPath "%LOCALAPPDATA%\Programs\MnemosyneC\resources\ollama"
  Add-MpPreference -ExclusionProcess "ollama.exe"
See: [FAQ link]
```

#### (b) `src/main/ollama_manager.ts` — Runtime Defender detection

If `_findBundledBinary()` returns `null` AND the parent directory `resources/ollama/` exists (meaning the installer placed something there, but the binary is gone) → emit IPC event `defender-quarantine-suspected` with user-visible message:

> "Windows Defender may have removed the bundled AI engine. Please add an exclusion and reinstall — see FAQ link."

This gives end users a recoverable error instead of a silent hang.

#### (c) Already done by Bishop SEG — Knight does NOT need to redo, but SHOULD verify

The following were completed by a parallel Bishop SEG before this addendum was written:

- `publish:win` was missing `prepare:ollama-binary` and `assert-floor-model` — **patched into `package.json`**.
- `scripts/assert-bundled-ollama-in-installer.mjs` written and verified (exits 1 if installer payload is missing the binary) — **already wired into `dist:win` and `publish:win`**.
- `asarUnpack: ["resources/ollama/**"]` is dead config (`extraResources` handles that path already) — Knight can remove or leave as-is; it is harmless.

Knight: verify these are present in the working tree before proceeding to installer.nsh work.

#### (d) Longer-term — NOT in v0.1.47 scope (Founder decision item)

A code-signing certificate ($200–$400/year OV, ~$1,000/year EV) eliminates this entire class of bug permanently. An EV cert also bypasses SmartScreen "Unknown Publisher" warnings at install time. Add to Founder decisions list.

---

### Bishop actions already taken on Founder's machine

Bishop has run the Defender exclusion on Founder's machine directly (parallel SEG, same BP080 session). Founder will reinstall v0.1.46 to verify the exclusion unblocks his use. If Founder's reinstall confirms the AI engine starts on v0.1.46 with the exclusion in place, that proves the root cause. v0.1.47 must then ship with the installer-side exclusion so end users do not have to apply it manually.

